449. quaecumque cluent, ‘whatever names these two things are called,’ i.e. whatever qualities are predicated of body and void. The subject, hae duae res, must be taken from the dat. which follows: for this constr., see n. to 1. 1 5. Lucr. seems here to translate a phrase of Epicurus in his discussion of this subject (Usener l. l. p. 22) ὅσα κατηγορεῖται σώματος (all the qualities that are predicated of body).
